{
  "What is the formula for calculating density?": "",
  "Density = Mass multiplied by Volume": "",
  "Density = Volume divided by Mass": "",
  "Density = Mass divided by Volume": "",
  "Density = Mass added to Volume": "",
  "Density is calculated by dividing the mass of an object by its volume: D = M / V. This tells you how much matter is packed into a given space.": "",
  "What is the standard unit of density for solids in the metric system?": "",
  "Grams per liter": "",
  "Grams per cubic centimeter": "",
  "Kilograms per meter": "",
  "Milliliters per gram": "",
  "The standard unit for the density of solids is grams per cubic centimeter (g/cm cubed). For liquids, grams per milliliter (g/mL) is commonly used, and 1 cm cubed = 1 mL.": "",
  "What is the density of pure water at room temperature?": "",
  "1.0 g/mL": "",
  "2.0 g/mL": "",
  "0.5 g/mL": "",
  "10 g/mL": "",
  "Pure water at room temperature has a density of approximately 1.0 g/mL (or 1.0 g/cm cubed). This value is commonly used as a reference point for comparing densities.": "",
  "An object has a mass of 50 grams and a volume of 25 cubic centimeters. What is its density?": "",
  "1,250 g/cm cubed": "",
  "0.5 g/cm cubed": "",
  "2.0 g/cm cubed": "",
  "75 g/cm cubed": "",
  "Using D = M / V: 50 g divided by 25 cm cubed = 2.0 g/cm cubed. The object has a density of 2.0 grams per cubic centimeter.": "",
  "If an object is less dense than water, what will happen when it is placed in water?": "",
  "It will sink to the very bottom": "",
  "It will float on the surface": "",
  "It will dissolve in the water": "",
  "It will hover in the middle area": "",
  "Objects less dense than water (density less than 1.0 g/mL) will float. Objects more dense than water will sink. This is why wood floats and rocks sink.": "",
  "Which of the following objects is the most dense?": "",
  "A cotton ball with very low mass": "",
  "A styrofoam cup that is very light": "",
  "A small steel ball bearing": "",
  "A wooden block of balsa wood": "",
  "Steel has a much higher density (about 7.8 g/cm cubed) than cotton, styrofoam, or balsa wood. Denser materials pack more mass into the same volume.": "",
  "Is density a physical property or a chemical property?": "",
  "It is a chemical property only": "",
  "It is a physical property only": "",
  "It is both chemical and physical": "",
  "It is neither chemical nor physical": "",
  "Density is a physical property because it can be measured and observed without changing the chemical composition of the substance.": "",
  "What tool is used to measure the volume of an irregularly shaped object?": "",
  "A ruler to measure the length and width": "",
  "A graduated cylinder using water displacement": "",
  "A balance to find the mass of the object": "",
  "A thermometer to measure the temperature": "",
  "Water displacement in a graduated cylinder is used to find the volume of irregularly shaped objects. You measure the water level before and after submerging the object, and the difference is the object's volume.": "",
  "If two objects have the same volume but different masses, which one is more dense?": "",
  "The one with a lower mass": "",
  "They have equal density": "",
  "The one with a higher mass": "",
  "Neither can be determined": "",
  "Since density = mass / volume, and the volume is the same for both objects, the object with the greater mass will have the greater density.": "",
  "What happens to the density of a substance if you cut it in half?": "",
  "The density is cut in half as well": "",
  "The density doubles in value": "",
  "The density stays exactly the same": "",
  "The density cannot be calculated now": "",
  "Density is an intensive property, meaning it does not change when the size or amount of the substance changes. Cutting an object in half reduces both mass and volume proportionally, keeping density the same.": "",
  "What is density?": "",
  "The total amount of space that an object takes up": "",
  "The amount of mass packed into a given volume": "",
  "The weight of an object measured using a balance": "",
  "The force of gravity acting on an object's mass": "",
  "Density is a measure of how much mass is contained in a given volume. It describes how tightly matter is packed together in a substance.": "",
  "What is mass?": "",
  "The total amount of space an object occupies in its container": "",
  "The pull of gravity that acts on an object sitting on Earth": "",
  "The amount of matter that makes up an object or substance": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance changes its state": "",
  "Mass is the amount of matter in an object, measured in grams or kilograms. Unlike weight, mass does not change based on location or gravity.": "",
  "What is volume?": "",
  "The total amount of matter contained inside an object": "",
  "The ratio of an object's mass to its overall size": "",
  "The force of gravity pulling on an object on Earth": "",
  "The amount of space that an object or substance occupies": "",
  "Volume is the amount of three-dimensional space an object or substance takes up, measured in units such as cubic centimeters, milliliters, or liters.": "",
  "What does 'water displacement' mean?": "",
  "Heating water until it completely evaporates from the container": "",
  "Measuring the water pushed aside by a submerged object's volume": "",
  "Pouring water from one container directly into another container": "",
  "Adding a chemical substance to water to change its temperature": "",
  "Water displacement is a method for finding the volume of an irregular object by measuring how much water it pushes aside when submerged. The rise in water level equals the object's volume.": "",
  "What is an intensive property?": "",
  "A property that changes depending on the amount of substance": "",
  "A property that does not change regardless of sample size": "",
  "A property that can only be measured using special equipment": "",
  "A property that requires a chemical reaction to be observed": "",
  "An intensive property does not depend on the amount of substance present. Density, color, and boiling point are all intensive properties that remain the same regardless of sample size.": "",
  "What does 'buoyancy' mean?": "",
  "The speed at which an object sinks to the bottom of a liquid": "",
  "The upward force a fluid exerts on an object placed in it": "",
  "The weight of an object measured while it is in the open air": "",
  "The amount of matter that a given container is able to hold": "",
  "Buoyancy is the upward force that a fluid (liquid or gas) exerts on an object placed in it. If the buoyant force is greater than the object's weight, the object floats.": "",
  "What is a graduated cylinder?": "",
  "A tool that measures the mass of an object in grams": "",
  "A tool that measures the temperature of a liquid sample": "",
  "A tool that measures the volume of a liquid accurately": "",
  "A tool that measures the density of a solid directly": "",
  "A graduated cylinder is a tall, narrow container with measurement markings used to accurately measure the volume of liquids. It can also be used for water displacement.": "",
  "What does 'meniscus' mean when measuring liquid volume?": "",
  "The curved surface of a liquid at its edge in a container": "",
  "The total volume of liquid poured into the measuring tool": "",
  "The marking on the outside of a graduated cylinder wall": "",
  "The density of the liquid being measured in the cylinder": "",
  "The meniscus is the curved surface of a liquid in a container. For water, it curves downward (concave), and you should read the volume at the bottom of the meniscus at eye level.": "",
  "What is an extensive property?": "",
  "A property that stays the same regardless of sample size": "",
  "A property that depends on the amount of substance present": "",
  "A property that identifies a substance by its chemical bonds": "",
  "A property that can only be observed during a phase change": "",
  "An extensive property depends on the amount of substance. Mass and volume are extensive properties because they change when you have more or less of a substance.": "",
  "What does 'directly proportional' mean when describing mass and volume for a substance?": "",
  "As mass increases, volume decreases at the exact same rate": "",
  "Mass and volume are completely unrelated to one another": "",
  "As mass increases, volume increases at a consistent rate": "",
  "Mass and volume always have the exact same numerical value": "",
  "For a given substance, mass and volume are directly proportional: as one increases, the other increases at a constant rate. The ratio of mass to volume (density) stays the same.": "",
  "A student has a rock with a mass of 30 g. She places it in a graduated cylinder containing 20 mL of water, and the water level rises to 32 mL. What is the density of the rock?": "",
  "0.94 g/mL": "",
  "1.50 g/mL": "",
  "2.50 g/mL": "",
  "1.88 g/mL": "",
  "First find the volume: 32 mL - 20 mL = 12 mL. Then use D = M/V: 30 g divided by 12 mL = 2.5 g/mL.": "",
  "A wooden block has a density of 0.6 g/cm cubed. Will it float or sink when placed in water (density = 1.0 g/cm cubed)?": "",
  "Sink, because wood is always heavier than water": "",
  "Sink, because its density is less than water": "",
  "Float, because its density is less than water": "",
  "Float, because its density is more than water": "",
  "The wooden block will float because its density (0.6 g/cm cubed) is less than the density of water (1.0 g/cm cubed). Objects less dense than the surrounding fluid will float.": "",
  "A student has a metal cube that measures 2 cm on each side and has a mass of 64 g. What is the density of the metal?": "",
  "16.0 g/cm cubed": "",
  "32.0 g/cm cubed": "",
  "8.0 g/cm cubed": "",
  "4.0 g/cm cubed": "",
  "First find the volume of the cube: 2 cm x 2 cm x 2 cm = 8 cm cubed. Then D = M/V: 64 g divided by 8 cm cubed = 8.0 g/cm cubed.": "",
  "Oil floats on top of water, and a coin sinks to the bottom of both liquids. What can you conclude about the densities of these three substances?": "",
  "Oil is densest, then water, then the coin material": "",
  "Water is densest, then oil, then the coin material": "",
  "All three substances have exactly the same density value": "",
  "The coin is densest, then water, then oil is least dense": "",
  "Since oil floats on water, oil is less dense than water. Since the coin sinks through both, the coin is denser than both. Order from most to least dense: coin > water > oil.": "",
  "A chef wants to know if a liquid is pure honey or honey mixed with water. Pure honey has a density of about 1.4 g/mL. The sample has a mass of 70 g and a volume of 60 mL. Is it pure honey?": "",
  "Yes, because the calculated density exactly matches pure honey": "",
  "No, the density of 1.17 g/mL is lower than pure honey's density": "",
  "Yes, because any liquid with mass over 50 g must be pure honey": "",
  "No, the density of 4.20 g/mL is higher than pure honey's value": "",
  "D = M/V = 70 g divided by 60 mL = 1.17 g/mL. Since pure honey is about 1.4 g/mL and this sample is only 1.17 g/mL, it is likely diluted with water, which has a lower density.": "",
  "A student needs to find the density of a small, oddly shaped stone. Which method should the student use to measure the stone's volume?": "",
  "Measure the length, width, and height with a ruler": "",
  "Use water displacement in a graduated cylinder": "",
  "Weigh the stone on a triple beam balance device": "",
  "Estimate the volume by looking at the stone closely": "",
  "Water displacement is the best method for irregularly shaped objects because you cannot calculate their volume using length times width times height. The displaced water volume equals the stone's volume.": "",
  "A substance has a density of 0.8 g/mL. A student pours it into a beaker of water. What would you expect to observe?": "",
  "The substance would sink below water and settle at the bottom": "",
  "The substance would float on top of water as a separate layer": "",
  "The substance would mix perfectly with the water in the beaker": "",
  "The substance would disappear completely when added to water": "",
  "Since the substance (0.8 g/mL) is less dense than water (1.0 g/mL), it will float on top of the water, forming a separate layer, similar to how oil floats on water.": "",
  "Two blocks are the same size, but Block A has a mass of 100 g and Block B has a mass of 200 g. How do their densities compare?": "",
  "Block A and Block B have equal densities since they are the same size": "",
  "Block A has double the density since it has half the mass of Block B": "",
  "Block B is twice as dense because it has double the mass in same volume": "",
  "Neither block has a density because their masses are too different here": "",
  "Since both blocks have the same volume but Block B has twice the mass, Block B has twice the density. D = M/V, so doubling the mass while keeping volume the same doubles the density.": "",
  "An ice cube (density 0.92 g/cm cubed) is placed in a glass of vegetable oil (density 0.91 g/cm cubed). What would happen?": "",
  "The ice would float on top of the oil because ice always floats": "",
  "The ice would sink because it is denser than the vegetable oil": "",
  "The ice would hover in the middle because they are same density": "",
  "The ice would dissolve instantly because oil melts ice quickly": "",
  "Even though ice floats in water, it would sink in vegetable oil because ice (0.92 g/cm cubed) is slightly denser than vegetable oil (0.91 g/cm cubed). An object sinks when it is denser than the surrounding fluid.": "",
  "A gold bar has a density of 19.3 g/cm cubed. A jeweler receives a bar claiming to be gold that has a mass of 500 g and a volume of 40 cm cubed. Is the bar likely real gold?": "",
  "Yes, because any bar with a mass of 500 g must be solid gold": "",
  "Yes, because the density of 12.5 g/cm cubed matches gold well": "",
  "No, the density is 12.5 g/cm cubed which is much less than gold": "",
